description:
In lichen_ipv6_addr_to_str() at lines 239-264:
```c
int ret = snprintf(buf, buflen, ...);

if (ret < 0) {
    // handle encoding error
    return -EIO;
}

if ((size_t)ret >= buflen) {
    LOG_ERR("truncated, need %d got %zu", ret, buflen);
    return -EINVAL;
}
```

snprintf returns the number of characters that WOULD have been written (excluding null terminator). If buflen is exactly 40 (LICHEN_IPV6_ADDR_STR_LEN), and the formatted string is exactly 39 characters:
- snprintf returns 39
- 39 >= 40 is FALSE
- We return 0 (success)

This is correct. The formatted IPv6 string is always exactly 39 characters (8 groups * 4 hex + 7 colons = 39). With buflen=40, snprintf writes 39 chars + null = 40 bytes total, using exactly buflen.

The check at lines 226-231 ensures buflen >= LICHEN_IPV6_ADDR_STR_LEN (40). So we'll never truncate.

NO BUG - the logic is correct.
